:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:159:\"One of the best ways to improve customer satisfaction with your website, as well as your ranking on popular search engines is to increase your website\'s speed.\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"Christopher Ross\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4474:\"<p>One of the best ways to improve customer satisfaction with your website, as well as your ranking on popular search engines is to increase your website&#8217;s speed but often as a web designer (or website owner) we have a false impression of the speed our website is operating at, simply because we&#8217;ve loaded it before.</p>\n<p>For example, if you load a website often your browser will store key information to speed up fetching the website in the future, such as DNS lookups and cached copies of images and text on the site. That&#8217;s why as web developers we&#8217;re often heard telling clients to <em>clear their browser cache</em> while previewing websites.</p>\n<h2>Waterfall View</h2>\n<p>That&#8217;s where a powerful tool like <a href=\"http://tools.pingdom.com/\">Pingdom Tools</a> comes in, it provides a fresh view of your website complete with an analytical overview of data such as this image of how long it takes to load thisismyurl.com.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-9761\" title=\"Results for thisismyurl from Pingdom Tools\" src=\"http://thisismyurl.com/files/2012/10/Results-for-thisismyurl-from-Pingdom-Tools.jpg\" alt=\"Results for thisismyurl from Pingdom Tools How to speed up your website with Pingdom Tools\" width=\"600\" height=\"356\" /></p>\n<p>Now, I&#8217;m able to quickly review a single page on my website and determine where the site is loading properly and where it can be improved, each colour in the image above reflects a different point part of the page loading process (DNS, Connect, Send, Wait, Receive) as well as the amount of time that it takes for the action to be completed.</p>\n<p>For example in the snap shot above, you can see that it takes almost no time for the styles.css page of thisismyurl.com to load at 10.7 kB but considerable time for the jquery.smoothscroll.js to load, even though it&#8217;s much smaller. There are a few ways to fix this, my first choice will be to <strong>add a minify plugin</strong> to my site which will combine all my JS files into a single, smaller load.</p>\n<h2>Load Time Analysis</h2>\n<p>The second portion of Pingdom Tools worth looking at to increase your site speed is the Load Time Analysis which will allow you to view an easy breakdown of all areas of your page load.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-9762\" title=\"Load Time Analysis\" src=\"http://thisismyurl.com/files/2012/10/Load-Time-Analysis.jpg\" alt=\"Load Time Analysis How to speed up your website with Pingdom Tools\" width=\"600\" height=\"315\" /></p>\n<p>You&#8217;ll notice for example that less than half of the content on my homepage comes from thisismyurl.com, the balance from other websites and services. Google Maps accounts for over 20% of the time spent loading my website, simply replacing the Google map with a graphical map would decrease my load times by 20%. For me, the answer was to find a graphic of the same area (I located one on a website and created my own version) and recreate it to highlight the same area the map did, while saving myself significant load time.</p>\n<p>I also noticed that 45% of the load time on my site is being used to load images, but the majority of these images are also coming from external services associated with the Google map and Facebook comments which had no reason to load on the homepage so I simply wrapped an is_single() check around the header code to ensure it only loads on the proper pages.</p>\n<h2>The Results</h2>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-9763\" title=\"Page Size results\" src=\"http://thisismyurl.com/files/2012/10/Page-Size-results.jpg\" alt=\"Page Size results How to speed up your website with Pingdom Tools\" width=\"600\" height=\"245\" /></p>\n<p>Overall, I&#8217;ve lowered the load time of my homepage from 3.5 seconds to 2.2 seconds, and I&#8217;ve lowered the overall weight from 1,100 kB to just over 600 kB. The number of unique files being loaded is down from 108 to 33. Â In all cases, these changes have improved the speed of my website while making it more responsive for both visitors and search engines.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/lal2fnJioZ_2uOnUQGZQ340WGkg/0/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/lal2fnJioZ_2uOnUQGZQ340WGkg/0/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a><br/>\n<a href=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/lal2fnJioZ_2uOnUQGZQ340WGkg/1/da\"><img src=\"http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/lal2fnJioZ_2uOnUQGZQ340WGkg/1/di\" border=\"0\" ismap=\"true\"></img></a></p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:81:\"http://thisismyurl.com/9759/how-to-speed-up-your-website-with-pingdom-tools/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"0\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:29:\"http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/\";