eaned up quite a bit since 3.8.9 was released last October</p>\n<p>We&#8217;ll be starting an educational series on developer-related changes and APIs that are available to you. Â But in the meantime, I do want to make sure you&#8217;re aware of someÂ <em>really importantÂ </em>changes in the latest 3.8.11 release.</p>\n<p>The version of jQuery shipping with WordPress (3.4 and greater) deprecates the usage of .live(), .bind() and .delegate() in favor of .on(). Â We&#8217;ve exerted a lot of effort in the 3.8.11 release cycle to bring our Javascript up to date with this practice. Â We also had some internal dependencies on a jQuery plugin called .livequery(). Â We&#8217;ve eliminated nearly every dependency on that in favor of .on() as well. Â The 3.8.12 release will likely see the .livequery() plugin removed from WPeC core.</p>\n<p><strong>If your plugin or theme depends on (or includes) an old version of Â jQuery, uses these deprecated methods, or depends on .livequery() &#8211; stuff is going to break. Â Update your plugins/themes.Â </strong></p>\n<p>We&#8217;ve also eliminated the dangerous practice of using eval() in Javascript. Â We were able to eliminate all but one instance, but that instance will eventually be removed.</p>\n<p><strong>If your theme or plugins hooks in to the &#8216;wpsc_alternate_cart_html&#8217; action to execute Javascript &#8211; this is now a bad practice. Â Please stop. Â We now have a custom JS event called &#8216;wpsc_fancy_notification&#8217; you can hook into instead.</strong></p>\n<p>Lastly, we&#8217;ve made the change in our Javascript to stop using &#8216;index.php&#8217; as an AJAX handler and have refactored everything to use the proper WordPress AJAX handler. Â You can (and should) do the same. Â If you&#8217;re unsure of how to properly develop AJAX functionality in core, the <a href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/AJAX_in_Plugins\">Codex has some great resources</a>. Â Also, you can look at how we&#8217;re doing it now.</p>\n<p>This post is intended to help our developer community along the path that we&#8217;re going down &#8211; a path moving towards cleaner code, more excellent standards and greater adherence to WordPress core conventions. Everything mentioned is something that we&#8217;ve dealt with in support since releasing 3.8.11 and will serve your communities and ours very well. Â If you have any questions, feel free to post in the comments and we&#8217;ll be glad to respond.</p>\n<p>Cheers!</p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"http://getshopped.org/news/theme-and-plugin-developers-listen-up/\">Theme and Plugin Developers, Listen Up!!</a> appeared first on <a href=\"http://getshopped.org\">GetShopped.org</a>.</p>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"http://getshopped.org/news/theme-and-plugin-developers-listen-up/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:38:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/\";a:1:{s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2:\"10\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\n		\n		\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:5:{s:0:\"\";a:7:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:42:\"WPeC 3.8.11.1 â Weâve Fixed Your Stuff\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:74:\"http://getshopped.org/getshopped-news/wpec-3-8-11-1-weve-fixed-your-stuff/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"comments\";a:1:{i